default4.2
default              
defaultA great deal of our members experience poorly integrated care from professionals who do not have a full understanding of the condition both at hospitals and in local provision.default4.3
default              
defaultOur survey website, DMDCentres.org
default and our Boys to Men Campaign 
defaultoutlined 
defaultthe
default massive drop off of servi
defaultces for adults living with DMD, especially in primary care such as physiotherapy, but also with cardiac and lung monitoring.
default4.3
default              
defaultProfessor Hanna
default’s
default recent report on unplanned admissions for Neuromuscular conditions found 
defaultthat 37% of them were avoidable and
default concluded by recommending that monitoring of known neuromuscular patients and coordination of care across sub-specialties would reduce such unnecessary stress on patients and their families, as well as reducing costs.
default4.4
default              
defaultAt the momentdefault,default care is failing families and patients defaultdue to lack of understanding and expertise. This is also costing the health service more money.default4
default.4
default 
default              
defaultAs set out in the Service Specification for Neuromuscular Services, patients should be reviewed by a multidisciplinary team (comprising of neuromuscular consultants, a neuromuscular physiotherapist, a neuromuscular nurse, an occupational therapist, a speech and language therapist, a dietician, a psychologist and a neuromuscular care coordinator) every 6 months, with some patients who have rapidly progressing neuromuscular conditions (like 
defaultDMD
default) being reviewed every 3 months.
default4.5
default              
defaultThe multidisciplinary team must also act as a hub, to facilitate access to colleagues including respiratory physicians, cardiologists, clinical geneticists, orthopaedic surgeons, endocrinologists, gastroenterologists, palliative care clinicians, occupational therapists and 
defaultorthotists
default. 
defaultThere must
default be a procedure with which feedback is given and processed to inform further care decisions.
default 
defaultIndeed, if there are specific problems with a patient involvin
defaultg one of these specialists, that specialist
default should be involved in the multidisciplinary reviews.
default E.g. The Standards of Care document states that from their early teens, people living with DMD should be seen at least twice a year for the monitoring of cardiac and lung function. 
default4
default.6
default              
defaultMultidisciplinary teams must ensure communication mechanisms exist between tiers 3, 2
default and 1 so that 
defaultlocal services such as
default physiotherapy, hydrotherapy, rehabilitation
default 
defaultare well informed 
defaultof patient’s requirements
default and the condition is monitored at a regular and local level.
default4.7
default 
default              
defaultA vital part of care from April 2013 for all those with 
defaultDMD and BMD
default will be the assigned patient-held records, written and updated by the multidisciplinary team. Such records will act as a ‘passport’ for proper care, allowing professionals who are not knowledgeable about the patients
default’
default needs, to understand how to care for patients. Only with regular updates of these records will these be of use, and so Action Duchenne reiterates the need for regular 
defaultMDT
default reviews of each patient.
default4.8
default              
defaultAction Duchenne is concerned about the amount of care that will be commissioned by Clinical Commissioning Groups (CCGs) for rare conditions, and which care will be commissioned nationally by NHS England (NHSE) and the 10 Local Area Teams (LATs). If CCGs are not responsible for improving outcomes for people living with DMD and BMD, then CCGs may neglect important primary care services and the ‘postcode lottery syndrome’ will prevail. It is also important to recognise that it is at primary level services such as physiotherapy where there are gaps. 
defaultCCGs need direction from NHSE and LATs on provision of services for rare conditions.default&#xa0;
